Many local community organizations are working together to offer Marin Community Learning Hubs during the 2020-21 school year. Marin Community Learning Hubs are safe spaces with adult supervision for TK-8th grade students. Students will receive connection support for distance learning and access to WiFi during school hours. This opportunity is offered FREE for families who meet specific criteria.

Eligible families qualify for free or reduced-price lunch, work with Department of Child and Family Services (DCFS), foster youth, newcomers, families unable to access or support distance learning, siblings, and those with special circumstances.

Click here to complete an Interest Survey: https://buff.ly/34xlygn
Haga clic aquí para completar una encuesta de interés: https://buff.ly/3jiztuZ

You can also complete a paper copy of the Interest Survey at your child’s school. If you have questions or would like support in completing the survey, please contact your school or email learninghubs@marinschools.org.

post_text:
California Approves Onsite Instruction for Children with Disabilities

Listen to this KQED podcast where you will hear about how the Marin County Office of Education's special education programs will be able to continue to support our students with special needs in person this academic year.

KQED Forum: Students with disabilities in California will be able to receive face-to-face instruction at schools this fall. Gov. Gavin Newsom and State Board of Education President Linda Darling-Hammond made the announcement Friday and acknowledged that some students with special needs are unable to adjust to distance learning. Families and students with learning disabilities and autism as well as students in foster care struggled when schools shut down last spring. We’ll hear about the unique challenges of remote learning for students with disabilities and what solutions are in the works.

post_text:
Check out the brand-new Let’s Talk Booklet – a comprehensive toolkit for navigating teen substance use in Marin County. Available in English and Spanish.

This brand-new resource includes information on how the teenage brain works, why substance use is a big deal, definitions of common substances, tips for providing support, and data about Marin County teens having easy access and the opportunity to use drugs and alcohol. This is a reality. But as parents and caregivers, we can help them navigate through these tough decisions.

Thank you Marin Prevention Network and the County of Marin Health and Human Services for partnering with Marin's schools to make this effort possible. All of Marin's 2,754 freshmen households will receive a copy in the mail!

Face coverings are required for everyone in Marin -- over 2 years old -- when around other people. This is especially important when:

1. at indoor AND outdoor businesses – whether as an employee or a customer
2. waiting in line to enter a store
3. waiting for and using public transit
4. riding in a taxi or rideshare (e.g., Lyft, Uber)
5. seeking healthcare; or visiting a hospital, medical clinic, pharmacy, laboratory, dental office, veterinary clinic or blood bank
6. walking outside and within 6 feet of others (6 feet = about the length of a mattress)

#maskupMarin

post_text:
Help those most in need during this challenging time! The Marin Community Foundation has established the COVID-19 Fund of MCF. This quick-response fund is dedicated to quickly directing financial support to nonprofit organizations serving those individuals and families most in need.

Members of our community have lost their jobs and are struggling to pay rent and buy nutritious food for their families. Older adults and people with disabilities who need nutrition, medical assistance and socialization are at great risk. Nonprofits that rely on volunteers to deliver services are finding themselves woefully shorthanded and are having to lay off staff.

If you are interested in supporting vital nonprofits in your community, know that MCF staff are constantly assessing the situation and are in an excellent position to direct funding to those who need it most.

Thank you for making a positive impact on our community! And thank you Marin Community Foundation!

post_text:
Thursday Night Family Group Support - Presented by Marin County Behavioral Health

Join a group of clinical staff and family partners who offer time each week to provide support, guidance, and a safe place to share your stories, connect with others who are having similar experiences, and provide education and information that may be helpful as you navigate the complexities of behavioral health challenges.

It is our goal to co-create an environment that fosters personal growth, self-awareness, and knowledge acquisition through compassion and honest conversation. Through this dialogue, we will address topics that that include numerous behavioral health related issues including, but not limited to:

Medications
How to recognize and compassionately respond to symptoms and behaviours
How to access mental health or substance use treatment services
Explanation of county BHRS services
Self-care strategies
Health boundary setting
Community resources
Common misconceptions

post_text:
Confronting Anti-Black Racism
PBS compiled materials for use with middle and high school students to help them understand the long history of anti-Black racism in the United States, and think about ways to address it in their own families and communities. Resources include news coverage of recent protests, videos on the origins of the Black Lives Matter Movement and protests against police brutality within the past decade, iconic PBS documentaries on the histories of race and racism in America, and activities addressing civic engagement and elevating students’ voices.

Confronting Anti-Black Racism
PBS compiled materials for use with middle and high school students to help them understand the long history of anti-Black racism in the United States, and think about ways to address it in their own families and communities. Resources include news coverage of recent protests, videos on the origins of the Black Lives Matter Movement and protests against police brutality within the past decade, iconic PBS documentaries on the histories of race and racism in America, and activities addressing civic engagement and elevating students’ voices.

PBSLEARNINGMEDIA.ORG
Confronting Anti-Black Racism | PBS LearningMedia

post_text:
Thank a healthcare worker today! Here is an amazing example of care, kindness, and heart in these challenging times.

Kaiser nurse Elena helped connect County Superintendent Mary Jane Burke to a teacher in ICU. She took the time to change into her protective gear, bring the phone to the teacher who is on a ventilator, and described the teacher's responses to her voice. It was heartwarming to hear that the teacher gave a thumbs up and kisses - showing strength and feeling loved.

To Elena and ALL #HealthcareHeroes...thank you! #carewithheart - Mary Jane Burke
text:
Thank a healthcare worker today! Here is an amazing example of care, kindness, and heart in these challenging times.

Kaiser nurse Elena helped connect County Superintendent Mary Jane Burke to a teacher in ICU. Join us January 29th for a free parent education workshop specifically targeted to parents of young children (ages 0-8).

Raising children in this digital age presents both great opportunities and significant challenges for parents and all those who care for young children. On January 29th at 6pm No Bully, a national leader in creating positive school climates and bully-proof schools, will present “Raising Young Children in a Connected World.” This workshop will provide parents with resources, tools, and guidance on how to help their children navigate the vast expanse of the digital world.

RSVP at https://nobullymcoe.eventbrite.com

CDC.GOV
Wildfire Smoke|Wildfires

Marin Health and Human Services
October 9, 2017 at 1:41 PM ·

Given the poor air quality due to wildfires in Northern California the Department of Marin Health and Human Services recommends that outdoor sporting activities be cancelled today, Monday October 9th and that children and all residents remain indoors and limit outdoor activities as much as possible.

Wildfires smoke can be harmful, and children, older adults, pregnant women, pets, and people with preexisting respiratory and heart conditions may be more likely to get sick if they breathe in wildfire smoke. For more information about protecting yourself from wildfire smoke, go to:
https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/wildfires/smoke.html

The Marin County Government has opened a temporary evacuation center at the Marin Veterans’ Memorial Auditorium, 10 Avenue of the Flags, in San Rafael. The temporary center (no cots or sleeping quarters available) serves as an overflow location for Sonoma and Napa fire evacuees, with capacity up to 2,000 people. For additional information visit MarinCounty.org.

Marin County Sheriff's Office
Marin County Office of Education

post_text:
If you are a student in 7th– 12th grade or are a college student in the Bay Area, we want YOU to bring your creativity to Hack 4 Health: Hackathon for Students, a health focused hackathon on April 1 in San Rafael.

DON'T CODE? DON'T WORRY! ALL 7th-12th grade and college students are encouraged to apply, REGARDLESS of coding expertise. Bring your creativity! Bring your enthusiasm for better health! And, bring your friends!
